Carrefour, Delhaize, Ferrovial, Natixis: European Equity Preview

-- B y   V i c t o r i a   T a y l o r
-- 
2011-08-05T04:00:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-04/carrefour-delhaize-ferrovial-natixis-pernod-european-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 3.5 percent to 243.16. The
Stoxx 50 Index dropped 3 percent to 2,327.94. The Euro Stoxx 50
Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro, decreased
3.4 percent to 2,412.29.  BP Plc (BP/)  : Transocean Ltd., the world’s largest
offshore driller, is in discussions with the  oil company  over
the 2010 Gulf of Mexico rig disaster that killed 11 workers and
triggered the worst offshore spill. The stock retreated 2.9
percent to 420.50 pence.  Carrefour SA (CA)  : Europe’s largest retailer said
Pierre-Jean Sivignon is joining from Royal Philips Electronics
to become chief financial officer. Sivignon will assume his
duties starting Sept. 1, replacing Pierre Bouchut, Carrefour
said in a statement today. Bouchut will be appointed Executive
Director, Growth Markets, starting Nov. 1. The shares of
Carrefour fell 3.5 percent to 18.57 euros.  Delhaize Group SA (DELB)  : The owner of the Food Lion
supermarkets in the U.S. may say second-quarter net income rose
to 118.8 million euros, according to the average of six analyst
estimates compiled by Bloomberg, from 114 million euros a year
earlier. Delhaize retreated 0.3 percent to 47.03 euros.  Dexia SA (DEXB)  :  Belgium ’s largest bank by assets
reported a record quarterly net loss of 4.03 billion euros,
which included a 377 million-euro pretax writedown of Greek debt
holdings, and said central-bank funding increased to about 34
billion euros at the end of June. Dexia decreased 1.5 percent to
1.66 euros.  Ferrovial SA (FER)  :  Spain ’s second-largest builder by
market capitalization said its Budimex unit bought Polish
railway builder PNI for 56 million euros ($79.3 million). The
shares dropped 3.7 percent to 8.12 euros.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  : Europe’s biggest lender by
market value sees more defaults from consumers and small
businesses during an upcoming “cooldown” of economic growth in
 Brazil , said Emilson Alonso, the bank’s head for  Latin America .
The shares fell 2.6 percent to 578.5 pence.  Natixis (KN)  SA: The investment-banking unit of  France ’s
second-largest bank by branches posted a less-than-estimated 3
percent drop in second-quarter profit to 505 million euros. The
shares fell 5.2 percent to 2.77 euros.  Pernod Ricard SA (RI FP): The world’s second-biggest liquor
maker lost an appeals court ruling in its 17-year battle with
Bacardi Ltd. over the right to use the name “Havana Club” on
rum in the U.S. market. The shares fell 3.9 percent to 64.20
euros.  Prudential Plc (PRU)  : The U.K.’s biggest insurer may
report first-half net income of 651 million pounds, according to
the average of two estimates compiled by Bloomberg. The shares
dropped 3.2 percent to 630 pence.  Royal Bank of Scotland Plc (RBS LN): The U.K.’s biggest
government-owned lender may report a first-half net loss of
786.6 million pounds, according to the average of five estimates
compiled by Bloomberg. The stock tumbled 6.1 percent to 30.28
pence.  Vinci SA (DG)  : The construction company and local
partners won a 210 million euro contract from the German
government to finance, design, widen, refurbish and maintain a
46.5 kilometer section of the A9 motorway linking Berlin and
Munich. The shares fell 5.1 percent to 35.60 euros.  -- With assistance from Rainer Buergin in Berlin, John Martens
in Brussels, Blanche Gatt in London, Sharon Smyth in Madrid and
Francois de Beaupuy and Gregory Viscusi in Paris; Editor:
